TITLE: Incorrect Example: Unnecessary Type Parameters TypeScript
DESCRIPTION: This example demonstrates incorrect usage of type parameters where the type parameter is only used once. The rule flags these as unnecessary. The first example shows a function `second` where type parameters `A` and `B` are declared but only `B` is effectively used multiple times. The second example uses a type parameter `T` in `parseJSON` only for the return type, which can be replaced with `unknown`. The third example has `T` and `K` used only once each.
SOURCE: https://github.com/typescript-eslint/typescript-eslint/blob/main/packages/eslint-plugin/docs/rules/no-unnecessary-type-parameters.mdx#_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: ts
CODE:
```
function second<A, B>(a: A, b: B): B {
  return b;
}

function parseJSON<T>(input: string): T {
  return JSON.parse(input);
